The '''80th Academy Awards''' ceremony, presented by the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] (AMPAS), honored the best [[2007 in film|films of 2007]] in the United States and took place February 24, 2008, at the [[Dolby Theatre|Kodak Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]] beginning at 5:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]] / 8:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]. During the ceremony, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences presented [[Academy Awards]] (commonly referred to as Oscars) in 24 categories. The ceremony, televised in the United States by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], was produced by [[Gil Cates]] and directed by Louis J, Horvitz.<ref name="Gil Cates">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/awards/2007/09/cates_tapped_for_record_14th_o.html|title=Cates tapped for record 14th Oscars telecast |last=O'Connor |first=Thomas |publisher=[[Sun Times Media Group]] |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=September 12, 2007|accessdate=May 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kivel|first1=Matthew|title=Oscar director back a 12th time|url=http://variety.com/2007/film/news/oscar-director-back-a-12th-time-1117978000/|accessdate=June 30, 2014|work=Variety|publisher=PMC|date=December 19, 2007}}</ref> Actor [[Jon Stewart]] hosted the show for the second time, having previously presided over the [[78th Academy Awards|78th ceremony]] held in 2006.<ref name="Jon Stewart host">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/12/movies/12stewart.html|title=Academy to Invite Jon Stewart Back as Oscar Host |last=Cieply |first=Michael |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 12, 2007|accessdate=May 28, 2013}}</ref> Two weeks earlier in a gala at the [[Beverly Wilshire Hotel]] in [[Beverly Hills, California]] held on February 9, the [[Academy Award for Technical Achievement|Academy Awards for Technical Achievement]] were presented by host [[Jessica Alba]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/techinnovations/2008-02-11-alba-tech-oscars_N.htm|title=Alba dazzles nerds at tech Oscars|accessdate=February 13, 2008|date=February 11, 2008|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|last1=Pearson|first1=Ryan}}</ref>

''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'' won four awards including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Halbfinger|first1=David|last2=Cieply|first2=Michael|title=‘No Country for Old Men’ Wins Oscar Tug of War|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/25/movies/awardsseason/25osca.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=September 21, 2008|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=February 25, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Burr|first1=Ty|title=Foreign accents Cotillard, Swinton, Bardem take top awards in a surprising night in Hollywood|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=February 25, 2008}}</ref> Other winners included ''[[The Bourne Ultimatum (film)|The Bourne Ultimatum]]'' with three awards, ''[[La Vie en Rose (film)|La Vie en Rose (La Môme)]]'' and ''[[There Will Be Blood]]'' with two awards, and ''[[Atonement (film)|Atonement]]'', ''[[The Counterfeiters (2007 film)|The Counterfeiters]]'', ''[[Freeheld]]'', ''[[The Golden Compass (film)|The Golden Compass]]'', ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'', ''[[Michael Clayton (film)|Michael Clayton]]'', ''[[The Mozart of Pickpockets]]'', ''[[Once (film)|Once]]'', ''[[Peter and the Wolf (2006 film)|Peter and the Wolf]]'', ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'', ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street (2007 film)|Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street]]'', and ''[[Taxi to the Dark Side]]'' with one. The telecast garnered under 32 million viewers, making it the least watched Oscar broadcast in history.

==Winners and nominees==
The nominations were announced on January 22, 2008, at the [[Samuel Goldwyn Theater]] in [[Beverly Hills, California]] by [[Sid Ganis]], president of the Academy, and actress [[Kathy Bates]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gray|first1=Tim|title=Oscar nominations announced|url=http://variety.com/2008/film/news/oscar-nominations-announced-1117979394/|accessdate=June 26, 2014|work=Variety|publisher=PMC|date=January 22, 2008}}</ref> ''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'' and ''[[There Will Be Blood]]'' tied for the most nominations with eight each.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=‘No Country’ and ‘There Will Be Blood’ Lead Oscars|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/23/movies/awardsseason/23oscarscnd.html?_r=1&hp&oref=slogin|accessdate=June 26, 2014|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=January 23, 2008}}</ref>

The winners were announced during the award ceremony of February 24, 2008.<ref name=Oscars2008>{{cite news|title=Nominees & Winners for the 80th Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html|accessdate=May 19, 2014|work=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|publisher=AMPAS|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20131012045551/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/2008/winners.html|archivedate=October 12, 2013}}</ref> Best Director winners [[Coen brothers|Ethan and Joel Coen]] became the second pair of directors to win the award for the same film. [[Jerome Robbins]] and [[Robert Wise]] first accomplished this feat for co-directing 1961's ''[[West Side Story (film)|West Side Story]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Coyle|first1=Jake|title=Oscars Honor Coens As Best Director(s)|url=http://www.foxnews.com/printer_friendly_wires/2008Feb25/0,4675,OscarsCoens,00.html|accessdate=June 27, 2014|work=[[Fox News]]|publisher=[[21st Century Fox]]|date=February 25, 2008}}</ref> For only the second time in Oscar history, all four acting winners were born outside the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neil|first1=Tom|title=Oscar invasion!|url=http://goldderby.latimes.com/awards_goldderby/2008/02/oscar-invasion.html|accessdate=April 11, 2008|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|date=February 24, 2008}}</ref> [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] became the eighth person to win Best Lead Actor twice.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neil|first1=Tom|title=Day-Lewis is 8th double Oscar lead actor|url=http://goldderby.latimes.com/awards_goldderby/2008/02/day-lewis-is-8t.html|accessdate=April 11, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|date=February 24, 2008}}</ref> Best Actress winner [[Marion Cotillard]] was the fifth person to [[List of actors nominated for Academy Awards for foreign language performances|win for a non-English speaking performance]] and the second person to do so in the aforementioned category.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gallo|first1=Phil|title=‘No Country’ big winner at Oscars|url=http://variety.com/2008/film/news/no-country-big-winner-at-oscars-1117981391/|accessdate=September 21, 2008|work=Variety|publisher=PMC|date=February 24, 2008}}</ref> [[Cate Blanchett]] became the eleventh performer to score [[List of actors nominated for two Academy Awards in the same year|double acting nominations in the same year]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Karger|first1=Dave|title=Blood, Sweat, and Cheers|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20173544,00.html|accessdate=February 3, 2008|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|date=January 25, 2008}}</ref> By virtue of her nomination for her role as [[Elizabeth I of England|titular character]] in ''[[Elizabeth: The Golden Age]]'', she also was the first actress and fifth performer overall to be nominated for portraying the same character in two different films (she previously earned a nomination for playing Queen Elizabeth I of England in 1998's ''[[Elizabeth (film)|Elizabeth]]'').<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neill|first1=Tom|title=Blanchett sets another first|url=http://goldderby.latimes.com/awards_goldderby/2008/01/blanchett-sets.html|accessdate=May 19, 2008|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|date=January 22, 2008}}</ref> Best Supporting Actor nominee [[Hal Holbrook]], who was 82 years and 339 days old at the time of his nomination, was the oldest Best Supporting Actor nominee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hal Holbrook Oldest Supporting Actor Nominee in Oscar History|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/01/22/hal-holbrook-oldest-supporting-actor-nominee-in-oscar-history/|accessdate=June 27, 2014|work=Fox News|publisher=21st Century Fox|date=January 22, 2008}}</ref> At age 98, art director [[Robert F. Boyle]] was the oldest recipient of the [[Academy Honorary Award]].<ref>{{cite news|title=45 Fun Facts About the Oscars|url=http://parade.condenast.com/130996/parade/oscar-fun-facts/|accessdate=June 27, 2014|work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|publisher=[[Condé Nast]]|date=February 26, 2012}}</ref>

